Authorization of appropriations for United States Customs Service for enhanced activities along the Southwest border. Authorization of appropriations for the United States Customs Service to enhance border investigative resources, combat drug smuggling and money laundering, process cargo efficiently, and reduce traffic waiting times on the Southwest border. Funding includes $467,320,000 for fiscal year 2002, $417,832,000 for fiscal year 2003, and additional funds as needed in subsequent years. $158,320,000 of the 2002 funds are allocated for acquisition and deployment expenses. In 2002, $158,320,000 is allocated for acquisition and deployment of narcotics enforcement, cargo processing, and counterterrorism technology along the Southwest border. This includes funding for various equipment such as mobile truck gamma ray systems, high energy pallet gamma ray systems, higher energy truck x-ray upgrades, nonintrusive inspection equipment operators, nonintrusive inspection technology maintenance, Industry Partnership Programs expansion, canine kennel construction, replacement of canines, automated targeting systems maintenance, and x-ray vans. $500,000 for replacement of canines;
$1,000,000 for automated targeting systems maintenance;
$2,500,000 for 10 x-ray vans;
$1,500,000 for 15 tool trucks;
$3,500,000 to refurbish and maintain existing x-ray vans and tool trucks;
$600,000 for 50 contraband detection kits;
$1,000,000 for 20 remote watch surveillance camera systems;
$1,000,000 for 40 counterspotter surveillance systems;
$2,500,000 for 10 truck license plate reader systems;
$1,600,000 for 40 narcotics particle detectors;
$14,800,000 for 29 land border vehicle targeting systems;
$3,000,000 for 250 under vehicle inspection systems;
$1,500,000 for 5 outbound passenger facilities and canopies;
$1,500,000 for 300 work station replacements. In addition to previous allocations, funds are designated for Customs Automated Operations System lanes, explosive vapor trace detectors, radiation detectors, identification devices, and detection training. A portion of the authorized amount is set aside for equipment maintenance and personnel training in subsequent fiscal years. The Commissioner of Customs may use funds allocated for equipment for new technologies that are technologically superior and cost-effective compared to specified equipment. In subsection (e), $79,000,000 in fiscal year 2002 and $172,000,000 in fiscal year 2003 are allocated for increased staffing in Southwest border enforcement. In subsection (e), funding is allocated for increased staffing in Southwest border enforcement, including inspectors, special agents, canine enforcement officers, and general support positions to reduce waiting times at entry points and combat drug smuggling and money laundering. Additionally, $230,000,000 in fiscal year 2002 and $230,000,000 in fiscal year 2003 are designated for infrastructure improvements at Customs Service facilities on the Southwest Border. These amounts are in addition to any other authorizations of appropriations. Amounts authorized for the United States Customs Service by subsection (a) are additional to any other appropriations authorized by law.
